ty Guide for Students","alternateName":"Road to Study in Turkey","publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/greeting-and-introduction-etiquette-guide-in-turkiye.webp","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/greeting-and-introduction-etiquette-guide-in-turkiye.webp","width":"1168","height":"880","caption":"Two people greeting from a distance on a traditional street with a warm hand gesture.","inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/greeting-and-introductions-in-turkey/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/greeting-and-introductions-in-turkey/","name":"A Guide to Greeting and Introductions Manners in Turkey","datePublished":"2025-10-02T15:33:48+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:40:46+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"primaryImageOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/greeting-and-introduction-etiquette-guide-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"A Guide to Greeting and Introductions Manners in Turkey","keywords":"Greeting and Introductions","datePublished":"2025-10-02T15:33:48+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:40:46+03:00","articleSection":"Cultural Adaptation","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Learn the etiquette for greeting and introductions in Turkey. Discover cultural norms and strengthen your social interactions!","name":"A Guide to Greeting and Introductions Manners in Turkey","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/greeting-and-introductions-in-turkey/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/greeting-and-introductions-in-turkey/#webpage"},"image":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/greeting-and-introduction-etiquette-guide-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/greeting-and-introductions-in-turkey/#webpage"}}]}]}'), '$.content_html', '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey, with its rich culture and social structure, has its own traditions in greeting and introductions. In this article, you will find detailed information about greetings in Turkey, common expressions used when getting acquainted, methods of meeting in social settings and things to consider about first impressions.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="greetings-in-turkey-handshake-hug-and-more">25 Essential Turkish Greetings and Phrases</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Starting a conversation in Turkish is easy with a simple greeting. The most versatile word is <strong>Merhaba!</strong> (Hello!), which you can use in almost any situation. For a more casual chat with friends or young people, you can simply say <strong>Selam!</strong> (Hi!).</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkish also has specific greetings for different times of the day. In the morning, you should say <strong>Günaydın!</strong> (Good morning!). As the day progresses, you can use <strong>İyi günler!</strong> (Good day!), which is excellent because it works for both greeting and saying goodbye. For the evening, use <strong>İyi akşamlar!</strong> (Good evening!), and when you&#8217;re parting late at night, say <strong>İyi geceler!</strong> (Good night!).</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Asking How Someone Is</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">After saying hello, it&#8217;s polite to ask how they are. Pay attention to the formality:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>For a formal or respectful context (like an elder or boss), use: <strong>Nasılsınız?</strong> (How are you? &#8211; Formal).</li>



<li>For friends and peers, use: <strong>Nasılsın?</strong> (How are you? &#8211; Informal).</li>



<li>A very casual phrase among close friends is <strong>Ne haber?</strong> (What&#8217;s up? / What news?).</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The standard, polite response is: <strong>İyiyim, teşekkür ederim.</strong> (I&#8217;m fine, thank you.). To ask the question back, you can say <strong>Ya siz?</strong> (And you? &#8211; Formal) or <strong>Ya sen?</strong> (And you? &#8211; Informal). If you want to say you&#8217;re fine too, use <strong>Ben de iyiyim.</strong></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Introducing Yourself</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">When you meet someone new, you&#8217;ll need to know these introduction phrases:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>To ask their name politely: <strong>Adınız ne?</strong> (What is your name? &#8211; Formal).</li>



<li>To state your name: <strong>Benim adım [İsim].</strong> (My name is [Name].).</li>



<li>After the exchange, always say: <strong>Memnun oldum.</strong> (Pleased to meet you.). A longer, more formal version is <strong>Tanıştığımıza memnun oldum.</strong> (It was nice meeting you.).</li>



<li>A great way to continue the conversation is to ask: <strong>Nereden geliyorsunuz?</strong> (Where are you from? &#8211; Formal). You can answer with: <strong>[Ülke]&#8217;den geliyorum.</strong> (I am from [Country].).</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Sayings Goodbye</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Just like greetings, there are different ways to say goodbye:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Hoşça kal(ın)!</strong> (Goodbye! / Stay well!) is used by the person who is <em>leaving</em>.</li>



<li><strong>Güle güle!</strong> (Goodbye! / Go happily!) is used by the person who is <em>staying</em> to the one who is leaving.</li>



<li>The most casual and common way to say goodbye is: <strong>Görüşürüz!</strong> (See you!).</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">These phrases will help you start conversations and show respect to Turkish speakers right away!</p>



